var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"Overview","text":""},{"location":"index.html#installation","title":"Installation","text":"<ol> <li>Download the ISO image.</li> <li>Flash it to a thumbdrive. (Or load the image into a virtual machine)</li> <li>Follow the installation guide</li> </ol>"},{"location":"index.html#basics","title":"Basics","text":""},{"location":"index.html#package-manager-pacman","title":"Package Manager: <code>pacman</code>","text":"<p><code>pacman</code> is a package manager of Arch Linux. (Similar to <code>apt</code> in Debian/Ubuntu)</p> <ul> <li>Installing package(s): <code>pacman -S [pkg1] [pkg2] ...</code></li> <li>Removing package(s): <code>pacman -R [pkg1]</code></li> <li>Updating repo database: <code>pacman -Sy</code></li> <li>Updating repo database + upgrade packages: <code>pacman -Syu</code></li> <li>Search for package: <code>pacman -Ss [pkg1]</code></li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#network-ip","title":"Network / IP","text":"<p>Display network interfaces.</p> <pre><code>ip a\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"index.html#setup","title":"Setup","text":"<p>The various setup guides are located here.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#tools-packages","title":"Tools &amp; Packages","text":"<p>The list of tools/packages used in the setup are located here.</p>"},{"location":"setup.html","title":"Setup","text":"<p>The setup would be split into a few sections:</p> <ul> <li>Terminal Setup: During the installation of the OS</li> <li>GUI Setup: After GUI has been setup</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tools.html","title":"Software/Tools","text":"<p>These are installed seperately apart from the base installation, which is quite barebone.</p>"},{"location":"tools.html#essential","title":"Essential","text":"<p>Typically, these should be installed during the installation/setup process.</p> Tool Description Installation sudo Gives user <code>superuser</code> permision to perform task. <code>sudo</code> does not come preinstalled, need to be installed and setup manually for the user. <code>pacman -S sudo</code> vim A terminal text editor, would be used to edit file configuration during the installation process. <code>pacman -S vim</code> nmtui A terminal application to configure IP network, useful for setting up network connection via terminal (before GUI is installed.) <code>pacman -S networkmanager</code>"},{"location":"tools.html#terminal","title":"Terminal","text":"<p>Terminal related packages.</p> Tool Description Installation tmux A terminal multiplexer. <code>pacman -S tmux</code> htop An interactive process viewer. <code>pacman -S htop</code> zsh Alternative to <code>bash</code> shell, this is actually optional. <code>pacman -S zsh zsh-completions</code>"},{"location":"tools.html#development","title":"Development","text":"<p>Development packages.</p> Tool Description Installation git A distributed version control system for tracking changes in source code during software development. <code>pacman -S git</code> curl A command-line tool and library for transferring data with URLs. It supports various protocols such as HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, and more. <code>pacman -S curl</code> wget A command-line utility for downloading files from the web. It supports downloading via HTTP, HTTPS, and FTP protocols, with options for recursive downloads and more. <code>pacman -S wget</code> rust A multi-paradigm programming language developed by Mozilla. Setup"},{"location":"tools.html#rust","title":"Rust","text":"<p>Setup via installation script.</p> <pre><code>curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tools.html#gui","title":"GUI","text":"<p>Graphical User Interface (GUI) related packages.</p> <ul> <li>lightdm</li> <li>xrandr</li> <li>feh</li> <li>i3</li> <li>i3lock-color</li> <li>polybar</li> <li>rofi</li> <li>terminator</li> <li>firefox</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tools.html#lightdm","title":"lightdm","text":"<p>X display manager, used to launch <code>i3</code>.</p> <p>The greeter is used to login into the i3 session.</p> <pre><code>sudo pacman -S lightdm lightdm-gtk-greeter\n</code></pre> <p>Enable the service.</p> <pre><code>sudo systemctl enable lightdm.service\n</code></pre> <p>After that, start the service.</p> <pre><code>sudo systemctl start lightdm.service\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tools.html#xrandr","title":"xrandr","text":"<p>Used to set screen resolution.</p> <pre><code>pacman -S xrandr\n</code></pre> <p>Getting display names</p> <p>Get the name of the display and the supported reolution to set.</p> <pre><code>xrandr\n</code></pre> <p>Setting the resolution</p> <p>For example, setting a display output of <code>1280x720</code> for <code>Display-1</code>.</p> <pre><code>xrandr --output Display-1 --mode 1280x720\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tools.html#feh","title":"feh","text":"<p>Lightweight image viewer, used to set the background wallpaper for <code>i3</code>.</p>"},{"location":"tools.html#i3","title":"i3","text":"<p>https://github.com/i3/i3</p> <p>A tiling window manager.</p> <p>Install the i3 package.</p> <p>Note: <code>i3</code> is a metapackage that would install the other packages (<code>i3-wm</code>, <code>i3blocks</code>, <code>i3lock</code>, <code>i3status</code>), install them all!</p> <pre><code>sudo pacman -S i3\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tools.html#i3lock-color","title":"i3lock-color","text":"<p>https://github.com/Raymo111/i3lock-color</p> <p>Replacement for <code>i3lock</code>, which looks much better that the default lockscreen.</p>"},{"location":"tools.html#polybar","title":"Polybar","text":"<p>https://github.com/polybar/polybar</p> <p>Replacement for <code>i3</code> status bar, which allows for a ton of customization.</p>"},{"location":"tools.html#rofi","title":"Rofi","text":"<p>https://github.com/davatorium/rofi</p> <p>Replacement for <code>i3 dmenu</code>, a dynamic menu to start applications.</p> <p>Note: Ensure that <code>yay</code> is setup beforehand!</p>"},{"location":"tools.html#terminator","title":"Terminator","text":"<p>A terminal emulator for GUI.</p> <pre><code>pacman -S terminator\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tools.html#firefox","title":"Firefox","text":"<p>A web browser.</p> <pre><code>pacman -S firefox\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"setup/gui.html","title":"GUI Setup","text":""},{"location":"setup/gui.html#setting-up-i3","title":"Setting up i3","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"},{"location":"setup/gui.html#setting-screen-resolution","title":"Setting screen resolution","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"},{"location":"setup/gui.html#setting-up-font-awesome","title":"Setting up Font Awesome","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"},{"location":"setup/term.html","title":"Terminal Setup","text":""},{"location":"setup/term.html#partition","title":"Partition","text":""},{"location":"setup/term.html#layout","title":"Layout","text":"<p>These are the main partitions that are used:</p> <ul> <li><code>/boot</code>: To store bootloader &amp; related files to boot the OS. GRUB is used as the bootloader.</li> <li><code>/</code>: The root directory of the Operating System (OS).</li> <li><code>/home</code>: Created a seperate partition for the user <code>/home</code> directory, so that the data could be isolated from the system data if anything goes wrong there.</li> <li><code>swap</code>: Used when the RAM is full. (Typically matches the amount of RAM one has. For example, if one has a 4GB RAM, a <code>swap</code> partition of 4GB is used.) </li> </ul>"},{"location":"setup/term.html#setting-the-partitions","title":"Setting the partitions","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"},{"location":"setup/term.html#user-setup","title":"User setup","text":""},{"location":"setup/term.html#account-creation","title":"Account creation","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"},{"location":"setup/term.html#adding-superuser-privileges","title":"Adding <code>superuser</code> privileges","text":"<p>Coming soon...</p>"}]}